WEBVTT

00:03.795 --> 00:04.921
Can I help you?

00:05.004 --> 00:06.214
{\an3}Yeah. We called
in a prescription

00:06.297 --> 00:07.382
{\an3}for clozapine
this afternoon.

00:07.465 --> 00:09.467
Name's Durning.

00:11.886 --> 00:13.972
{\an1}He's gonna see there are
no refills allowed.

00:16.516 --> 00:18.309
Check it out.

00:18.393 --> 00:20.562
This prescription
doesn't allow for a refill.

00:20.645 --> 00:22.272
Right. When I called in
this afternoon,

00:22.355 --> 00:23.732
I explained that her doctor
is out of town

00:23.815 --> 00:24.691
{\an3}and, uh...

00:24.774 --> 00:26.568
Probably has a service.
You want me to try it?

00:26.651 --> 00:30.321
No. Uh, that is,
we need the pills now.

00:30.405 --> 00:32.156
Nothing I can do.

00:33.074 --> 00:34.284
{\an1}I'm sorry.

00:37.871 --> 00:38.788
Let's go, let's go.

00:38.872 --> 00:39.998
Go, go, go, go.

00:40.081 --> 00:41.082
{\an3}PHARMACIST:
Hey, come back here!

00:41.166 --> 00:42.375
Is there a problem?

00:42.459 --> 00:44.586
Yeah.

00:45.754 --> 00:47.797
{\an1}Bigger than
you can imagine.

00:52.302 --> 00:54.012
♪♪

00:54.095 --> 00:57.348
♪♪

00:57.432 --> 00:59.309
♪♪

00:59.392 --> 01:00.810
It just feels
right, okay?

01:00.894 --> 01:03.313
{\an3}Us being together--
to me, it feels right.

01:03.396 --> 01:05.648
You and I together?
We've been together.

01:05.732 --> 01:07.776
Yeah, and as I recall,
it was pretty great, wasn't it?

01:07.859 --> 01:09.152
(sighs)
I knew I shouldn't have gone

01:09.235 --> 01:10.987
to that Valentine's Day party
with you.

01:11.070 --> 01:12.655
Or come on the radio last week.

01:12.739 --> 01:14.073
Or kissed you.

01:14.157 --> 01:15.325
But you did.

01:15.408 --> 01:16.951
And I think we both know why.

01:17.035 --> 01:18.036
{\an1}Yes.

01:20.413 --> 01:22.832
Because we're going through
some tough times right now.

01:22.916 --> 01:24.334
And that's it?

01:24.417 --> 01:26.503
Yeah.

01:26.586 --> 01:27.504
Most of it.

01:27.587 --> 01:29.672
Most, but not all.

01:29.756 --> 01:32.592
Most is a lot for two people

01:32.675 --> 01:35.303
that are thinking about
getting together.

01:37.263 --> 01:39.057
Okay.

01:39.140 --> 01:43.353
Well, um, would...

01:43.436 --> 01:45.522
some of you
like to go on a date?

01:45.605 --> 01:47.357
{\an3}Some oYeah.

01:47.440 --> 01:50.777
You know, the-the part that
wants us to get back together,

01:50.860 --> 01:52.403
the smart part.

01:52.487 --> 01:53.530
(chuckles)

01:53.613 --> 01:56.449
Very funny.

01:59.786 --> 02:01.454
Say yes.

02:03.331 --> 02:04.707
No.

02:04.791 --> 02:06.376
Why, because you don't want to?

02:06.459 --> 02:07.877
Because I can't.

02:07.961 --> 02:11.297
♪ I'll do anything ♪

02:11.381 --> 02:13.341
♪ For you ♪

02:13.424 --> 02:15.260
(sighs)

02:17.303 --> 02:19.389
♪ We'll get through
these times... ♪

02:19.472 --> 02:21.224
Buy you a drink?

02:21.307 --> 02:23.226
Uh, not right now.

02:23.309 --> 02:25.562
Donna, we have to talk.

02:25.645 --> 02:26.729
I know.

02:26.813 --> 02:28.231
I'm just,
I'm not ready yet, okay?

02:28.314 --> 02:31.359
I want you to level
with me, okay?

02:31.442 --> 02:33.236
Did we break up
because of somebody else?

02:33.319 --> 02:37.282
What?!

02:37.365 --> 02:39.450
{\an1}Well, you and David looked
awful cozy up in that booth.

02:39.534 --> 02:42.537
{\an3}Look, you are the one that
fooled around, not me.

02:42.620 --> 02:43.580
That's the whole point.

02:43.663 --> 02:45.915
{\an1}Just makes no sense
how we broke up over nothing.

02:45.999 --> 02:46.916
I don't know.

02:47.000 --> 02:49.127
{\an3}You and Gina looked
pretty cozy that night.

02:49.210 --> 02:52.422
{\an3}And if you hadn't passed
out, I mean... what?

02:52.505 --> 02:53.715
Nothing happened.

02:53.798 --> 02:54.757
Yeah, it did.

02:54.841 --> 02:57.051
You lost my trust.

03:08.688 --> 03:10.857
♪ ♪

03:37.550 --> 03:39.802
♪ ♪

04:03.576 --> 04:05.620
♪ ♪

04:41.948 --> 04:44.409
(Matt sighs)

04:44.492 --> 04:46.911
{\an1}I'm telling you, it's the most
frustrating thing ever.

04:46.995 --> 04:48.204
I can imagine.

04:48.287 --> 04:50.581
And I've begged, pleaded...

04:50.665 --> 04:51.708
I even tried to steal.

04:51.791 --> 04:53.084
That's how desperate we are.

04:53.167 --> 04:56.587
You know, I use to work
at this clinic,

04:56.671 --> 04:59.549
and I knew these two patients--
one had cancer and one had AIDS.

04:59.632 --> 05:01.467
{\an3}And both of them
were trying to get

05:01.551 --> 05:04.470
their hands on some drugs
that had been banned here.

05:04.554 --> 05:05.555
So, were theNo.ble to or...?

05:05.638 --> 05:07.932
So they went down to Mexico
and they bought them,

05:08.016 --> 05:09.559
and they smuggled them
back across the border.

05:09.642 --> 05:11.060
I know it's illegal,

05:11.144 --> 05:12.562
but you said you were desperate.

05:12.645 --> 05:14.022
Yeah, and willing to do

05:14.105 --> 05:15.565
the wrong thing
for the right reason.

05:15.648 --> 05:18.401
So maybe I can call them
and they can give me

05:18.484 --> 05:20.236
the names of people
who can help you.

05:20.319 --> 05:22.030
Uh, I don't know.

05:22.113 --> 05:24.407
I mean,
it sounds great, except...

05:24.490 --> 05:26.409
I-I-I can't take
Lauren with me.

05:26.492 --> 05:28.578
{\an1}And I, and I can't
leave her here.

05:28.661 --> 05:30.204
Why?
Is she getting worse?

05:30.288 --> 05:31.414
No, but she's out of pills,

05:31.497 --> 05:33.082
and now it's only
a matter of time.

05:33.166 --> 05:34.417
I'm sorry.

05:34.500 --> 05:35.376
{\an1}It's like

05:35.460 --> 05:37.420
she'll go in and out
at first, you know?

05:37.503 --> 05:40.423
She'll have, like, this really--
I don't know-- bizarre moment,

05:40.506 --> 05:41.758
{\an1}and the next thing
you know,

05:41.841 --> 05:44.594
she's, like, totally normal.

05:44.677 --> 05:46.637
Once it starts, though, she'll
be overwhelmed pretty quickly.

05:48.347 --> 05:51.434
I don't know; thanks for
the Mexican angle though.

05:51.517 --> 05:53.561
There really is
nothing I can do.

05:53.644 --> 05:56.481
Yeah, I guess not.

05:56.564 --> 05:58.608
{\an3}But maybe there's
something I can do.

06:02.737 --> 06:04.238
You're opening
your own gym?

06:04.322 --> 06:06.616
{\an3}That, uh, sounds
expensive.

06:06.699 --> 06:07.450
Yeah, it is.

06:07.533 --> 06:10.286
{\an1}But I'm borrowing
against my trust fund.

06:10.369 --> 06:11.496
You have a trust fund?

06:11.579 --> 06:12.497
Yeah, well,

06:12.580 --> 06:14.415
it's called exhibition fees.

06:14.499 --> 06:17.251
Basically, it's money I earned
skating while I was a minor.

06:17.335 --> 06:19.003
I asked my mom
to bring the paperwork.

06:19.087 --> 06:20.463
Did you earn a lot?

06:20.546 --> 06:21.798
Well, not by
Beverly Hills standards,

06:21.881 --> 06:25.134
but I did okay for trash.

06:25.218 --> 06:26.260
Gina, we've been over this.

06:26.344 --> 06:27.428
I never should have said that.

06:27.512 --> 06:28.805
But you did.

06:28.888 --> 06:30.598
Well, I was upset
about you and Noah.

06:30.681 --> 06:33.810
Donna, there is no me and Noah.

06:33.893 --> 06:36.104
I know, but you need
to understand that

06:36.187 --> 06:37.480
{\an3}the way that
it looked

06:37.563 --> 06:40.441
and what
I thought happened, I...

06:40.525 --> 06:43.444
I just, I'm gonna need a little
bit of time to get over that.

06:43.528 --> 06:45.780
Okay.

06:45.863 --> 06:47.490
Yeah, I-I understand.

06:48.533 --> 06:49.909
(doorbell rings)

06:54.789 --> 06:55.748
Mom...

06:55.832 --> 06:58.626
There's my baby girl.

06:58.709 --> 07:00.795
{\an3}Mmm... Say hi
to(gasps)

07:00.878 --> 07:02.296
Oh...

07:02.380 --> 07:03.297
{\an3}look who's
all grown up.

07:03.381 --> 07:05.299
(both chuckle)

07:05.383 --> 07:06.551
You look great.

07:06.634 --> 07:08.010
Oh, thanks.

07:08.094 --> 07:10.638
Another 10 pounds and I'll
match my driver's license.

07:10.721 --> 07:12.557
(laughs)

07:12.640 --> 07:16.394
Oh, isn't this
just a slice of heaven?!

07:16.477 --> 07:17.770
{\an3}Mom, did you bring
the trust information?

07:17.854 --> 07:19.522
It is sheer heaven.

07:19.605 --> 07:21.357
I tell you, sheer heaven.

07:22.775 --> 07:25.528
Mom, I just asked you if you
brought the trust stuff.

07:25.611 --> 07:27.071
Oh, I'm sorry.

07:27.155 --> 07:28.573
I completely forgot, honey.

07:28.656 --> 07:30.741
I told you it was important.

07:30.825 --> 07:32.410
And I told you I was sorry.

07:32.493 --> 07:35.413
{\an1}Aunt Bobbi, why don't
you sit down and relax?

07:35.496 --> 07:38.374
Oh, thanks.

07:40.626 --> 07:43.629
{\an1}The trust was set up
here, you know.

07:43.713 --> 07:44.380
A place called

07:44.463 --> 07:46.632
Cooper, Adams and Savin.

07:46.716 --> 07:49.385
{\an3}Yeah, yeah, I-I...
I know them.

07:49.468 --> 07:51.470
{\an3}Uh, my dad has a couple
accounts there.

07:51.554 --> 07:53.055
{\an1}Oh, will you take me
there later?

07:53.139 --> 07:54.557
{\an3}Yeah, sure.

07:56.517 --> 07:59.061
Celebrity trash?

07:59.145 --> 08:00.730
What kind of story is that?

08:00.813 --> 08:02.899
{\an1}Actually,
what we do is kidding.

08:02.982 --> 08:04.066
we target a celebrity

08:04.150 --> 08:05.568
and go through
a day's worth

08:05.651 --> 08:07.737
of their trash
and publish what we find.

08:07.820 --> 08:08.905
I'd read that artiMom.

08:08.988 --> 08:10.907
He, he is kidding.

08:10.990 --> 08:12.408
Steve, tell my parents
you're kidding.

08:12.491 --> 08:15.411
Have I mentioned what
a great reporter Janet is?

08:15.494 --> 08:18.039
How smart and diligent she is?

08:18.122 --> 08:20.583
Oh, Steve's just, uh,
he's just impressed

08:20.666 --> 08:23.211
that I occasionally insist
we base our stories in fact.

08:23.294 --> 08:25.254
{\an3}No, no, working with her
is really great.

08:25.338 --> 08:28.049
Which is why I was a little
worried when we started to...

08:28.132 --> 08:31.219
{\an3}Working together
even more...

08:31.302 --> 08:34.222
{\an3}...than we already
are because

08:34.304 --> 08:36.349
that would mean...

08:37.515 --> 08:39.434
Yeah.lot of work.

08:39.519 --> 08:41.437
What I meant to say was

08:41.520 --> 08:43.438
Well, Steve's,

08:43.522 --> 08:44.440
Steve's a great boss.

08:44.524 --> 08:46.275
Which is great

08:46.359 --> 08:48.611
because that's what he is--

08:48.694 --> 08:51.447
{\an3}my boss.

08:51.530 --> 08:53.908
But being a reporter
is an honorable profession.

08:53.991 --> 08:57.453
{\an1}Why degrade
the story with...

08:57.536 --> 08:58.788
garbage?

08:58.871 --> 09:00.915
{\an3}Well, they're not
stories about garbage.

09:00.998 --> 09:02.458
They're stories about secrets.

09:02.541 --> 09:05.586
And it's amazing what people
don't want revealed.

09:05.670 --> 09:07.797
{\an1}I think people
deserve their privacy.

09:07.880 --> 09:08.965
So do I.

09:09.048 --> 09:11.509
And I think people
hide way too much.

09:11.592 --> 09:13.552
I couldn't agree with you more.

09:20.768 --> 09:22.436
{\an3}Oh!

09:22.520 --> 09:24.272
Hey. We still on
for this afternoon?

09:24.355 --> 09:25.481
Mm-hmm. Hmm?

09:25.564 --> 09:27.108
Uh, my trust, remember?

09:27.191 --> 09:28.526
You're gonna go with me
to Cooper, Adams, and Savin.

09:28.609 --> 09:31.320
Yeah, sure, this afternoon.

09:33.698 --> 09:36.450
She's cute.

09:36.534 --> 09:38.077
Yeah, I suppose.

09:38.160 --> 09:40.538
{\an3}I mean, if you like
tall, thin and perfect

09:40.621 --> 09:41.831
bone structure but, you know.

09:43.582 --> 09:45.001
So, we're set?

09:45.084 --> 09:46.460
Yes, day after tomorrow.

09:46.544 --> 09:47.878
I'm looking forward to it.

09:49.213 --> 09:52.133
Gina, Donna, this
is Deborah Fowler.

09:52.216 --> 09:53.968
Hi. Wait...

09:54.051 --> 09:55.678
<i>the</i> Deborah Fowler?

09:55.761 --> 09:56.887
The sex therapist?

09:56.971 --> 09:58.139
The one that wrote

09:58.222 --> 09:59.473
all the how-to books
on relationships?

09:59.557 --> 10:00.599
I'm afraid so.

10:00.683 --> 10:01.726
Oh-ho...

10:01.809 --> 10:03.477
{\an1}The station's pairing
us up for a show.

10:03.561 --> 10:05.396
{\an5}They said if it goes
well, they'll make it
something permanent.

10:06.772 --> 10:08.190
Listen, I have to go.

10:08.274 --> 10:10.526
Okay, I'll give you a call,
we'll talk about the show...

10:10.609 --> 10:13.195
{\an1}I'm looking
forward to it.

10:13.279 --> 10:15.364
{\an1}Me, too.

10:19.952 --> 10:21.537
{\an1}DAVID:
Oh!t?

10:21.620 --> 10:23.664
{\an3}No, nothing,
it's just, um...

10:26.500 --> 10:28.544
You know that...
that-that thing

10:28.627 --> 10:33.132
that you asked me
to do last night?

10:33.215 --> 10:34.175
That thing?

10:34.258 --> 10:37.887
You know, the, the thing
that you asked me to do

10:37.970 --> 10:39.555
that I said I couldn't do.

10:42.183 --> 10:45.478
The thing you couldn't do.

10:45.561 --> 10:46.562
The thing!

10:46.645 --> 10:51.400
{\an1}Yeah, yeah, yeah,
what about it?

10:51.484 --> 10:53.402
Well, as it turns out, I can.

10:53.486 --> 10:54.695
Mm-hmm.

10:54.779 --> 10:55.571
Good..

10:55.654 --> 10:56.405
Good.

10:56.489 --> 10:57.698
OAll right.

10:57.782 --> 10:59.575
Yeah.

10:59.658 --> 11:02.244
Uh, when you're ready to go to
the bank, I'll be at the store.

11:02.328 --> 11:03.579
{\an1}Okay.reat.

11:03.662 --> 11:05.247
Um... See you.

11:05.331 --> 11:06.540
{\an1}Okay.

11:09.001 --> 11:10.753
{\an1}You're going out
on a date with Donna?

11:10.836 --> 11:12.421
Oh.

11:12.505 --> 11:14.507
No. It's-It's not...

11:18.010 --> 11:19.595
Actually, yeah.
Yeah, we are.

11:19.678 --> 11:22.556
{\an1}Oh, well, um,
that's-that's cool.

11:22.640 --> 11:24.600
{\an4}I mean, you don't have
to be embarrassed or
anything about it.

11:24.683 --> 11:27.395
{\an1}It's not like you were
plotting Noah's overthrow.

11:28.646 --> 11:29.480
Is it?

11:29.563 --> 11:32.233
No. No, it isn't.

11:32.316 --> 11:34.443
(laughing):
Oh... wow.

11:34.527 --> 11:35.945
Has anyone ever told you

11:36.028 --> 11:38.280
{\an1}that you're
an adorably bad liar?

11:40.074 --> 11:41.784
It's nothing.

11:41.867 --> 11:44.203
Uh-huh.

11:44.286 --> 11:45.663
It's nothing.

11:46.664 --> 11:49.291
Okay.

11:49.375 --> 11:51.168
Donna and I went out
on Valentine's Day.

11:51.252 --> 11:53.421
You did?

11:54.505 --> 11:55.506
{\an3}No.

11:55.589 --> 11:57.800
No, we didn't do that.

11:57.883 --> 11:58.759
{\an3}We...

11:58.843 --> 12:01.512
kissed.

12:01.595 --> 12:02.805
You kissed?!

12:02.888 --> 12:08.477
{\an1}Okay. Uh, so I guess one thing
is just kind of...

12:08.561 --> 12:10.479
leading to the next?

12:10.563 --> 12:13.065
Yeah. Yeah, I guess so.

12:19.989 --> 12:21.449
Well, I got a map here
of the stars' homes.

12:21.532 --> 12:23.784
We'll target the ones based on
their easily accessible trash

12:23.868 --> 12:25.870
and then we're off.

12:26.871 --> 12:28.122
Did you hear me?

12:28.205 --> 12:29.498
Unfortunately.

12:29.582 --> 12:31.375
{\an1}(sighs)
You know, Janet,

12:31.459 --> 12:33.461
technically, I'm the one who
should be angry about lunch.

12:33.544 --> 12:35.629
{\an3}I told you I
wanted to go alone.

12:35.713 --> 12:37.339
{\an1}Yeah, but you didn't
tell me why.

12:37.423 --> 12:38.716
You know, if you're embarrassed

12:38.799 --> 12:40.509
{\an1}to tell you know
your parents about me,

12:40.593 --> 12:42.011
{\an1}the least you could do
is say so.

12:42.094 --> 12:43.471
I'm not embarrassed.

12:43.554 --> 12:45.139
You wouldn't let me touch you.

12:45.222 --> 12:47.475
Touching's fine.

12:47.558 --> 12:49.018
But you-you pawed me.

12:49.101 --> 12:50.811
Aw, come on.

12:50.895 --> 12:53.314
You're complaining because
I wanted to hold your hand?

12:53.397 --> 12:55.524
{\an3}Look, my-my father's
traditional.

12:55.608 --> 12:57.693
{\an1}So? Does that mean
you can't have a boyfriend?

12:57.776 --> 12:59.028
No, of course I can.

12:59.111 --> 13:01.530
Then you are embarrassed.

13:01.614 --> 13:02.573
No.

13:02.656 --> 13:05.367
{\an1}Then what? It is
about me, isn't it?

13:05.451 --> 13:07.536
In a way.

13:07.620 --> 13:09.872
{\an3}But, um, just
not how you think.

13:09.955 --> 13:11.248
What other way is there?

13:11.332 --> 13:12.500
(sighs)

13:12.583 --> 13:16.545
My father just wants me to be
with someone who's Japanese.

13:16.629 --> 13:17.713
Oh.

13:17.796 --> 13:21.550
{\an3}And he doesn't approve of
me dating anyone who isn't.

13:28.349 --> 13:29.642
WOMAN:
<i>Mm-hmm. Thank you.</i>

13:32.061 --> 13:34.730
{\an3}Hi. Uh, I'm, uh,
Gina Kincaid

13:34.813 --> 13:36.565
{\an3}and this is my cousin
Donna Martin.

13:36.649 --> 13:39.568
We're here about a trust account
that was opened in Gina's name

13:39.652 --> 13:40.736
about eight years ago.

13:40.819 --> 13:42.196
{\an1}I just want to find out
how much is in it.

13:42.279 --> 13:44.240
I know that I can't have
the money until I'm 25,

13:44.323 --> 13:47.284
but I want to use it
as collateral for this gym

13:47.368 --> 13:48.577
that I'm going to open.

13:48.661 --> 13:50.412
Mm-hmm.

13:50.496 --> 13:51.288
Oh, here Great.

13:51.372 --> 13:54.208
I figure there's
about $75,000 in there.

13:55.376 --> 13:56.293
Am I close?

13:56.377 --> 13:57.419
Actually, there's less.

13:57.503 --> 13:59.088
{\an1}Yes.less?

13:59.171 --> 14:04.051
Currently in the account,
there's $14,216.

14:05.636 --> 14:06.428
Wait.

14:06.512 --> 14:08.264
$14,000?

14:08.347 --> 14:09.598
...216.

14:09.682 --> 14:11.934
I'm sorry, I think
there's been some mistake.

14:12.017 --> 14:13.227
Could you check again?

14:13.310 --> 14:15.437
Well, I'm sorry,
but that's not really necessary.

14:15.521 --> 14:17.773
Wait a minute-- I know
that I earned at least

14:17.856 --> 14:20.067
$60,000...

14:20.150 --> 14:22.486
{\an3}and with any kind
of investment portfolio,

14:22.570 --> 14:25.239
there has to be
some way that...

14:25.322 --> 14:27.575
If there was ever that kind
of money in this account,

14:27.658 --> 14:28.867
it's not there anymore.

14:38.335 --> 14:39.920
{\an3}So let me get
this straight now.

14:40.004 --> 14:42.464
